# Wildcard Matching

## Solution 1: Recursion Approach

### Intuition
* At first glance, the pattern matching looks simple when there are only normal characters — we can check them one by one.  
* It becomes interesting because of two wildcards:  
  * `?` matches exactly one character.  
  * `*` matches zero or more characters.  
* When a `*` appears, we get branching behavior — it can represent an empty sequence or extend to consume several characters.  
* These branching paths hint that recursion can naturally explore all possibilities.  
* The recursive idea arises by comparing characters from the end of the string and pattern, and handling special symbols accordingly.  
* If both reach the beginning simultaneously, we found a complete match. If one ends early (and the other isn’t full of `*`), it cannot fully match.

### Approach
* Compare characters of the string and pattern from the end.  
* When the current characters match or the pattern has `?`, move one step back in both strings.  
* When the pattern has `*`, explore both cases — matching zero characters (move pattern backward) or matching one/more characters (move string backward).  
* Continue this recursion until both are completely processed.  
* Ensure base cases handle empty strings and patterns properly, considering that leftover `*` can still form a match.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```pseudocode
function wildCardMatching(i, j, s, p) {
    /* Base case: if both string and pattern are completely checked */
    if i == -1 {
        if j == -1 {
            return true /* Full match found */
        }
        if p[j] == '*' {
            /* '*' can match zero characters */
            return wildCardMatching(i, j - 1, s, p)
        }
        return false /* Pattern has unmatched characters */
    }

    /* Base case: pattern finished but string not */
    if j == -1 {
        return false
    }

    /* Case 1: current characters match or pattern has '?' */
    if s[i] == p[j] or p[j] == '?' {
        return wildCardMatching(i - 1, j - 1, s, p)
    }

    /* Case 2: pattern has '*' */
    if p[j] == '*' {
        /* '*' matches zero or multiple characters */
        matchZero = wildCardMatching(i, j - 1, s, p)
        matchMore = wildCardMatching(i - 1, j, s, p)
        return matchZero or matchMore
    }

    /* Case 3: no match */
    return false
}
