## Solution 4: Space Optimization

### Intuition
* Observing the tabulation version, each row depends only on the previous row and current computations.  
* Hence, we can store only two arrays — one for the previous state and one for the current state — instead of the entire 2D table.  
* This reduces memory while keeping correctness intact.

### Approach
* Maintain two boolean arrays: `prev` (previous row) and `curr` (current row).  
* Initialize `prev[0] = true` because empty string and pattern match.  
* Fill pattern’s `*` handling into the first row (`prev`).  
* For every new row, compute values based on `prev` and current pattern, then replace `prev` with `curr`.  
* After processing all rows, the final answer lies in the last cell of `curr`.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```pseudocode
/* Function to perform wildcard matching using space optimization */
wildCardMatching(s, p) {
        /* Initialize variables */
        m = size of s /* Length of string */
        n = size of p /* Length of pattern */

        /* Create two arrays for previous and current row states */
        prev[n + 1] = {0}, curr[n + 1] = {0}

        /* Base case: Empty string matches empty pattern */
        prev[0] = 1

        /* Initialize the first row for patterns starting with '*' */
        for j from 1 to n {
            if (p[j - 1] == '*') {
                prev[j] = prev[j - 1] /* '*' can match zero characters */
            } else {
                prev[j] = 0
            }
        }

        /* Process the string and pattern */
        for i from 1 to m {
            curr[0] = 0 /* Empty pattern cannot match a non-empty string */

            for j from 1 to n {
                /* Case 1: Characters match or pattern has '?' */
                if (s[i - 1] == p[j - 1] or p[j - 1] == '?') {
                    curr[j] = prev[j - 1] /* Carry forward the match */
                }
                /* Case 2: Pattern has '*' */
                else if (p[j - 1] == '*') {
                    curr[j] = prev[j] or curr[j - 1] /* '*' matches zero or more characters */
                }
                /* Case 3: No match */
                else {
                    curr[j] = 0
                }
            }
            /* Update prev to current row for the next iteration */
            prev = curr
        }

        /* The final answer is stored in the last cell of prev */
        return curr[n]
}

