# Combination Sum

## Solution

### Intuition

* Each valid combination is built by **choosing some numbers and skipping others**, while trying to reach the target sum.
* To avoid duplicate combinations, first sort the array so equal values come together; this makes it easy to **skip repeated choices at the same decision level**.
* Then explore possibilities step by step:

  * pick a number and continue with the remaining part of the array,
  * or move ahead without picking it.
* Keep track of the current sum:

  * if it becomes exactly the target, we found one valid combination,
  * if it goes beyond the target, this path cannot work, so stop exploring it.
* Since each element can be used only once, after choosing an element we continue only with the elements that come after it.

### Approach - Backtracking

- Sort the input array first to easily handle duplicates.

- Use a backtracking approach to explore all combinations, ensuring each number is used only once in the combination and skipping duplicates.

- Track the current combination and sum while recursively attempting to add elements.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```
backtrack(start, currentCombination, currentSum, result) {
    if (currentSum == target) { 
        /* If currentSum matches target, add the current combination to the result */
        result.append(currentCombination.copy())
        return  
    }
    /* If the current sum exceeds the target */
    if (currentSum > target) {  
        /* no valid combination */
        return  
    }
    for (i from start to len(arr)) {  
        /* Check for duplicates */
        if (i > start and arr[i] == arr[i - 1]) {  
            /* Skip this iteration if the current element is the same as the previous one */
            continue  
        }
        /* Add the current element to the combination */
        currentCombination.append(arr[i])  
        /* Recursively call backtrack with updated parameters */
        backtrack(i + 1, currentCombination, currentSum + arr[i], result)  
        /* Remove the last added element to backtrack */
        currentCombination.pop()  
    }
}

findUniqueCombinations(arr, target) {
    /* Sort the array to handle duplicates easily */
    sort(arr)  
    /* Initialize an empty list to store the unique combinations */
    result = []  
    backtrack(0, [], 0, result) 
    return result  
}

```
