# Filter Linked List Nodes by Array

## Solution

### Intuition

* We need to remove every node whose value appears in the given array, so the first useful idea is to make checking those values very fast.
* A set lets us quickly decide whether a node should stay or be deleted while scanning the linked list only once.
* A dummy node makes deletion easier, especially when the first node itself must be removed.

### Approach

* Store all values from the array in a set for fast lookup.
* Attach a dummy node before the linked list so deletion at the front is handled in the same way as deletion in the middle.
* Traverse the list from the dummy node and skip every next node whose value is present in the set.
* Return the list starting after the dummy node.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={20} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
deleteNodes(head, arr) {
    valuesToDelete = hash set created from arr  /* Store all values that must be removed */

    dummy = new Node(0)      /* Dummy node before head */
    dummy->next = head
    current = dummy          /* current always points to the node BEFORE the node being checked */

    while (current->next != null) {
        /* Check the next node's value (because deleting needs prev pointer) */
        if (valuesToDelete contains current->next->data) {
            /* Next node should be deleted: skip it */
            current->next = current->next->next
        } else {
            /* Next node is fine: move forward */
            current = current->next
        }
    }

    return dummy->next  /* New head after deletions */
}
