# Linked List Partitioning  

## Solution

### Intuition

* The main job is not to sort the list. We only need all smaller values to appear first while keeping the original order inside both groups.

* A clean way to do this is to collect nodes into two separate chains while walking through the list once.

* This works because every node is added to the end of its correct chain in the same order it appears, so the required order is preserved automatically.

### Approach

* Create one temporary list for nodes with values smaller than the given number and another temporary list for the remaining nodes.

* Traverse the original list once and place each node at the end of the correct temporary list.

* Finish the second temporary list so that no old link accidentally remains attached.

* Connect the first temporary list to the second temporary list and return the new starting node.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```pseudocode
partitionList(head, x) {
    /* Create dummy starting nodes so both groups can be built easily */
    lessHead = new Node(0)
    greaterHead = new Node(0)

    /* Keep tail pointers to append nodes while preserving order */
    less = lessHead
    greater = greaterHead

    /* Visit every node once and place it into the correct group */
    while head != null {

        /* If the current value is smaller, extend the first group */
        if head->data < x {

            /* Attach the current node to the end of the first group */
            less->next = head

            /* Move the tail pointer of the first group forward */
            less = less->next
        } else {

            /* Otherwise, extend the second group */
            greater->next = head

            /* Move the tail pointer of the second group forward */
            greater = greater->next
        }

        /* Move to the next node from the original list */
        head = head->next
    }

    /* End the second group to avoid keeping any unwanted old link */
    greater->next = null

    /* Join the first group with the second group */
    less->next = greaterHead->next

    /* Return the first real node of the rearranged list */
    return lessHead->next
}
```

