# Sort with Minimum Swaps

## Solution

### Intuition

* Since all elements are distinct, every value has exactly one correct position in the sorted array.

* So after sorting a copy of the array, we can directly know the final position of each value.

* If a value is not sitting at its correct index, we can swap it with the element currently present at that correct index.

* Repeating this keeps fixing positions one by one, and each swap places at least one element correctly.

### Approach

* Make a copy of the array and sort it to know the final order.

* Store the correct sorted position of every value in a map.

* Traverse the original array. If the current element is already at its correct index, move ahead.

* Otherwise, swap it with the element at its correct index and count that swap. Keep doing this until every position becomes correct.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={21} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```pseudocode
minSwaps(arr) {
    n = length of arr

    /* Create a sorted copy to know the final position of every value */
    sortedArr = copy of arr
    sort(sortedArr)

    /* Store the final sorted index of each value */
    position = HashMap()
    for (i = 0 to n - 1) {
        position[sortedArr[i]] = i
    }

    swaps = 0
    i = 0

    /* Keep placing each value into its correct sorted index */
    while (i < n) {
        if (position[arr[i]] == i) {
            i = i + 1
        } else {
            correctIndex = position[arr[i]]
            swap(arr[i], arr[correctIndex])
            swaps = swaps + 1
        }
    }

    return swaps
}
```

</CodeBlock>

