## Solution 2: Monotonic Increasing Stack

### Intuition

* While moving from left to right, many previous elements can never become the answer for future positions.

* If a previous element is greater than or equal to the current value, it cannot be the nearest smaller element for this position or for any later smaller-or-equal value, so it can be removed.

* A stack helps keep only the useful candidates in increasing order.

* After removing all invalid candidates, the top of the stack becomes the nearest smaller element on the left.

### Approach

* Maintain a stack that stores useful previous elements.

* Traverse the array from left to right.

* While the top of the stack is greater than or equal to the current element, pop it.

* If the stack is not empty after popping, its top is the nearest smaller element. Then push the current element into the stack.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={20} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```pseudocode
nearestSmallerElement(arr) {
    n = length of arr

    /* Stack stores useful previous values */
    stk = empty stack
    ans = array of size n filled with -1

    for (i = 0 to n - 1) {

        /* Remove all elements that cannot be the answer */
        while (stk is not empty and stk.top() >= arr[i]) {
            stk.pop()
        }

        /* If stack still has elements, the top is the nearest smaller one */
        if (stk is not empty) {
            ans[i] = stk.top()
        }

        /* Current value may help future elements */
        stk.push(arr[i])
    }

    return ans
}
```

