# Convert Postfix to Prefix

## Solution

### Intuition

* In postfix form, every operator comes after its two operands, so we cannot directly place it at the front of the expression.

* A stack helps us store operands and already built partial expressions until an operator is ready to use them.

* Whenever we see an operand, we simply push it because it may become part of a bigger expression later.

* Whenever we see an operator, the top two stack entries are the right and left parts of that operator, so we combine them in prefix order and push the new expression back.

### Approach

* Create an empty stack of strings.

* Traverse the postfix expression from left to right.

* If the current character is an operand, push it into the stack.

* Otherwise, pop the top two strings, build `operator + left + right`, and push that new string back. The final stack top is the required prefix expression.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={18} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```pseudocode
postfixToPrefix(s) {
    /* Create an empty stack to store operands and intermediate expressions */
    stk = empty stack

    /* Process each character from left to right */
    for (i = 0 to length of s - 1) {

        /* If current character is an operand, push it directly */
        if (s[i] is operand) {
            stk.push(s[i])
        } else {

            /* Top element becomes right operand and next becomes left operand */
            rightPart = stk.top()
            stk.pop()
            leftPart = stk.top()
            stk.pop()

            /* Build prefix expression and push it back */
            stk.push(s[i] + leftPart + rightPart)
        }
    }

    /* Final stack top is the complete prefix expression */
    return stk.top()
}
```

