# Convert Prefix to Postfix 

## Solution

### Intuition

* In a prefix expression, every operator appears before the two parts it combines, so reading from left to right does not give enough information immediately.

* If we process the expression from right to left, operands become available before the operator that needs them.

* A stack is useful here because it can store ready-made parts of the answer until an operator combines them into a larger postfix expression.

* This works because every time we see an operator, the top two stored parts are exactly the left and right pieces that belong to it.

### Approach

* Move through the expression from right to left.

* Put every operand into a stack because it may be used later.

* When an operator is found, remove the top two expressions, join them in postfix order, and put the new expression back.

* After the full scan, the top of the stack is the final postfix expression.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={18} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```pseudocode
prefixToPostfix(s) {
    /* Create a stack to store operands and partial postfix expressions */
    stk = empty stack

    /* Process the prefix expression from right to left */
    for (i = length of s - 1 to 0) {

        /* If the current character is an operand, store it directly */
        if (s[i] is operand) {
            stk.push(s[i])
        } else {

            /* Remove the left and right parts needed by this operator */
            leftPart = stk.top()
            stk.pop()
            rightPart = stk.top()
            stk.pop()

            /* Build the postfix form and store it back */
            stk.push(leftPart + rightPart + s[i])
        }
    }

    /* The remaining stack top is the full postfix expression */
    return stk.top()
}
```

