# Convert Infix to Prefix

## Solution

### Intuition

* Prefix is hard to build directly from an infix expression because operators can appear between operands and inside nested brackets.

* A cleaner idea is to reverse the infix expression first and swap every opening bracket with a closing bracket.

* After that, the problem becomes very similar to building a postfix expression using a stack.

* Once that postfix form is built for the reversed expression, reversing it gives the required prefix expression.

### Approach

* Reverse the given infix string and swap `(` with `)` and `)` with `(`.

* Traverse this modified string from left to right and use a stack to process operators and brackets.

* Add operands directly to the output, and handle operators using precedence rules while keeping the correct associativity for `^`.

* After finishing the traversal, pop all remaining operators, then reverse the output string to get the final prefix expression.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={26} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```pseudocode
infixToPrefix(s) {
    /* Reverse the infix expression */
    reverse(s)

    /* Swap opening and closing brackets */
    for (i = 0 to length of s - 1) {
        if (s[i] == '(') {
            s[i] = ')'
        } else if (s[i] == ')') {
            s[i] = '('
        }
    }

    stk = empty stack
    output = empty string

    /* Build postfix for the reversed expression */
    for (each ch in s) {
        if (ch is operand) {
            output += ch
        } else if (ch == '(') {
            stk.push(ch)
        } else if (ch == ')') {
            while (stk is not empty and stk.top() != '(') {
                output += stk.top()
                stk.pop()
            }
            stk.pop()
        } else {
            if (ch == '^') {
                while (stk is not empty and stk.top() != '(' and priority(ch) <= priority(stk.top())) {
                    output += stk.top()
                    stk.pop()
                }
            } else {
                while (stk is not empty and stk.top() != '(' and priority(ch) < priority(stk.top())) {
                    output += stk.top()
                    stk.pop()
                }
            }
            stk.push(ch)
        }
    }

    /* Add all remaining operators */
    while (stk is not empty) {
        output += stk.top()
        stk.pop()
    }

    /* Reverse postfix to get prefix */
    reverse(output)
    return output
}
