# Beauty of all Substrings 

## Solution

### Intuition

* The beauty of one substring depends only on how many times each character appears inside it.

* If we fix the starting position and extend the substring one character at a time, we can keep updating the same frequency count instead of rebuilding it from scratch.

* After each extension, we only need the largest and smallest non-zero frequency to get the beauty of the current substring.

* This checks all substrings in a direct way, and it stays practical here because there are only lowercase English letters.

### Approach

* Start each substring from every possible position in the string.

* For one fixed start, keep extending the ending position and update the character counts as new letters are included.

* After each extension, scan the frequency list to find the largest and smallest non-zero counts.

* Add that beauty value to the running total and continue until all substrings are covered.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={25} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```pseudocode
beautyOfSubstring(s) {
    /* Store the string length and total beauty sum */
    n = length of s
    ans = 0

    /* Try every position as the starting point of a substring */
    for (i = 0 to n - 1) {

        /* Reset character counts for the new starting point */
        arr = array of size 26 filled with 0

        /* Extend the substring one character at a time */
        for (j = i to n - 1) {

            /* Update the frequency of the newly included character */
            arr[s[j] - 'a'] = arr[s[j] - 'a'] + 1

            /* Add the beauty of the current substring to the answer */
            ans = ans + beauty(arr)
        }
    }

    /* Return the sum of beauty values of all substrings */
    return ans
}

beauty(arr) {
    /* Start with the widest possible min and an empty max */
    mini = infinity
    maxi = 0

    /* Check all lowercase letters to find non-zero min and max frequency */
    for (i = 0 to 25) {
        if (arr[i] != 0) {
            mini = minimum of mini and arr[i]
            maxi = maximum of maxi and arr[i]
        }
    }

    /* Return the beauty of the current substring */
    return maxi - mini
}
