# City Tower Placement Puzzle

## Backtracking

### Intuition

If you try to place towers randomly on a grid while making sure they can’t monitor each other, you’ll quickly notice that placing one tower affects future choices-it blocks its column and two diagonals.

A natural way to handle this is to place towers row by row, checking only safe spots for each step. If you get stuck in a row with no safe positions, you can backtrack, remove the last tower, and try a different spot.

Repeating this trial-and-error process until all rows are filled eventually covers every possible safe arrangement, which is exactly how this backtracking method works.

### Approach

* Place one tower per row using backtracking.

* For each spot, check that its column and both diagonals are free; if not, skip it.

* When a spot is chosen, mark its column and diagonals, move to the next row; if blocked later, undo and try the next spot.

* When every row has a tower, record the current grid as a valid arrangement.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```
/* Size of the city grid (n x n) */
size                                
/* Stores all valid tower arrangements */
solutions           

/* Convert the current state matrix (2D char array) into a vector of strings */
createTowerMatrix(state) {
    /* Stores the converted matrix */
    mat                     
    for (row = 0 to size-1) {
        /* Convert row to string and Add the row string to the matrix */
        currentRow(state[row].begin(), state[row].end())  
        mat.push_back(currentRow)          
    }
    /* Return the string representation */
    return mat                              
}

/* Backtracking function to place towers so that no two monitor each other */
backtrack(row, diagonals, antiDiagonals, cols, state) {
    /* If all rows are filled, a valid tower arrangement is found */
    if (row == size) {
        /* Store the arrangement */
        solutions.push_back(createTowerMatrix(state))   
        return
    }
    /* Try placing a tower in each column of the current row */
    for (col = 0 to size-1) {
        /* Represents one diagonal direction */
        currDiagonal = row - col 
        /* Represents the other diagonal direction */
        currAntiDiagonal = row + col                

        /* Skip if another tower can already monitor this position */
        if (cols.count(col) || diagonals.count(currDiagonal) || antiDiagonals.count(currAntiDiagonal)) {
            continue
        }

        /* Mark this position as monitored */
        cols.insert(col)
        diagonals.insert(currDiagonal)
        antiDiagonals.insert(currAntiDiagonal)
        /* Place the tower */
        state[row][col] = 'T'                            

        /* Move to the next row to place the next tower */
        backtrack(row + 1, diagonals, antiDiagonals, cols, state)

        /* Remove the tower and monitoring marks (backtrack) */
        cols.erase(col)
        diagonals.erase(currDiagonal)
        antiDiagonals.erase(currAntiDiagonal)
        state[row][col] = '.'
    }
}

/* Solve the City Towers placement problem for a given grid size */
solveCityTowers(n) {
    /* Store grid size */
    size = n                                            
    /* Create an empty grid */
    emptyMat(size, vector<char>(size, '.'))  
    backtrack(0, empty set, empty set, empty set, emptyMat)
    /* Return all valid arrangements */
    return solutions                                    
}

