## Counting Sort Approach

### Intuition

Because every item weighs at most 1,000 units, we can avoid sorting and still pick the lightest items first by using a simple “counting” trick:

1. Go through all the items once and keep a tally of how many items weigh 1 unit, how many weigh 2 units, and so on up to the heaviest weight.

2. Then, starting at weight 1, take as many items of that weight as you can without pushing the total over 5,000 units.

3. Move on to weight 2, then weight 3, and so on, always stopping as soon as even one more item of the current weight would exceed the limit.

4. The moment you can’t take at least one more item of a given weight, you’re done, your count is the maximum possible.

Because the heaviest weight is only 1,000, counting and then scanning those 1,000 buckets runs in time roughly proportional to the number of items. However, if weights could be huge (say up to 10⁹), you couldn’t afford an array that large, this approach only works when the maximum weight stays small.

### Approach

* Find the highest weight to know the full range of weights.

* Record how many items there are for each weight.

* From the lightest weight upward, take as many items as will fit under the limit.

* Stop when no more items can fit and return the total taken.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```
maxItemCount(weight) {
    /* Determine the heaviest item to size our counts array */
    maxWt = -1
    for (each wt of weight) {
        maxWt = max(maxWt, wt)
    }
    /* Create a frequency array where counts[wt] = number of items weighing wt */
    array counts(maxWt + 1)
    for (each wt of weight) {
        counts[wt]++
    }
    /* ans: total items we can take, units: total weight accumulated */
    ans = 0
    units = 0
    /* Iterate through each possible weight from lightest (i=0) up to max */
    for (i = 0 to maxWt) {
        if (counts[i] != 0) {
            /* Determine how many items of weight i we can still take without exceeding the 5000-unit limit */
            take = min(counts[i], (5000 - units) / i)
            /* If even one item of this weight doesn't fit, we must stop */
            if (take == 0) {
                break
            }
            /* Add the weight of the taken items to our total */
            units += take * i
            /* Increment answer by how many items we took at this weight */
            ans += take
        }
    }
    /* Return the maximum number of items that fit within the limit */
    return ans
}
```

