# Merge K Sorted Linked Lists

## Solution 1: Iterative Merging Using Pairwise Comparison

### Intuition

* When faced with several sorted linked lists, a natural first thought is to merge them one by one in order.  
* Merging two sorted lists is a known and simple task — just compare their heads and link the smaller one.  
* We can extend this idea: start with the first list, then merge each of the remaining lists into it sequentially.  
* The main challenge is performance — each merge grows the resulting list, making the later merges more expensive.  
* Even though it is not the most efficient solution, this technique builds a clear base idea which is easy to implement and reason about.

### Approach

* Start by initializing a merged list using the first linked list in the input collection.  

* Define a helper function to merge two sorted linked lists efficiently using a dummy node.  

* In this helper function, compare the heads of both lists and attach the smaller one to the current pointer.  

* Continue this process until one of the lists is completely traversed, then attach all remaining nodes from the other list.  

* Use this helper repeatedly to merge each list into the current merged result.  

* Return the final merged list after all linked lists are processed.  

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```pseudocode
mergeTwoLists(head1, head2) {
    /* Initialize pointers for both lists */
    temp1 = head1
    temp2 = head2

    /* Create a dummy node to simplify insertion */
    dummy = new Node(0)
    cur = dummy

    /* Traverse both lists while both have nodes */
    while (temp1 != null and temp2 != null) {
        /* Compare current values and attach the smaller one */
        if (temp1.data <= temp2.data) {
            cur.next = temp1
            temp1 = temp1.next
        } else {
            cur.next = temp2
            temp2 = temp2.next
        }

        /* Move the current pointer forward */
        cur = cur.next
    }

    /* Attach remaining nodes if any list is not empty */
    if (temp1 != null) cur.next = temp1
    else cur.next = temp2

    /* Return the merged list excluding dummy node */
    return dummy.next
}

mergeKLists(arr) {
    /* Handle edge cases */
    k = arr.size()
    if (k == 0) return null
    if (k == 1) return arr[0]

    /* Initialize merged list as first list */
    head = arr[0]

    /* Sequentially merge each list */
    for i = 1 to k - 1 {
        head = mergeTwoLists(head, arr[i])
    }

    /* Return fully merged result */
    return head
}
```

